HOUSE BILL DRH40672-MGa-162A
Short Title: RURAL Care Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Reeder.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENACT THE REVITALIZING, UPLIFTING REGIONS & ACCESS LOCAL
3 (RURAL) CARE ACT TO PROVIDE FOR THE CREATION OF A RURAL
4 HEALTHCARE INFRASTRUCTURE FUND AND A RURAL HEALTHCARE
5 INFRASTRUCTURE PROGRAM TO BE ADMINISTERED BY THE NORTH
6 CAROLINA STATE HEALTH COORDINATING COUNCIL; TO DIRECT THE NORTH
7 CAROLINA STATE HEALTH COORDINATING COUNCIL TO DEVELOP A PLAN
8 FOR THE ESTABLISHMENT AND ADMINISTRATION OF THE RURAL
9 HEALTHCARE INFRASTRUCTURE PROGRAM; TO REPEAL THE RURAL HEALTH
10 CARE STABILIZATION PROGRAM; AND TO AMEND THE COMPOSITION AND
11 DUTIES OF THE NORTH CAROLINA STATE HEALTH COORDINATING COUNCIL.
12 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
13
14 PART I. RURAL HEALTHCARE INFRASTRUCTURE FUND
15 SECTION 1.1.(a) Chapter 131E of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
16 Article to read:
17 "Article 4A.
18 "Rural Healthcare Infrastructure Fund."
19 SECTION 1.1.(b) G.S. 131A-32 is recodified as G.S. 131E-74 in Article 4A of
20 Chapter 131E of the General Statutes, as enacted by subsection (a) of this section, and reads as
21 rewritten:
22 "§ 131E-74. The Rural Health Care Stabilization Healthcare Infrastructure Fund.
23 (a) Legislative Intent. – The General Assembly recognizes the need to establish and
24 maintain a sufficient funding source to address the ongoing capital and healthcare infrastructure
25 needs of the State. The General Assembly further recognizes the need to protect the State's
26 substantial improvements in existing healthcare facilities while providing a stable funding source
27 to pay for new facilities to meet the needs of a growing rural population.
28 (b) Creation and Source of Funds. – The Rural Health Care Stabilization Healthcare
29 Infrastructure Fund is created as a nonreverting special fund in the Office of State Budget and
30 Management. Department of Health and Human Services to provide financial assistance in the
31 form of grants and loans at below market interest rates with structured repayment terms to support
32 the construction, renovation, or modernization of healthcare infrastructure located in rural areas
33 of the State. The Fund shall operate as a revolving fund consisting of funds appropriated to, or
34 otherwise received by, the Rural Health Care Stabilization Healthcare Infrastructure Program and
35 all funds received as repayment of the principal of or interest on a loan made from the Fund. The
36 North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council shall administer the Fund. The State Treasurer
*DRH40672-MGa-162A*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 is the custodian of the Fund and shall invest its assets in accordance with G.S. 147-69.2 and
2 G.S. 147-69.3. Moneys in the Fund shall only be used for loans made pursuant to this Article.
3 (c) Use of Funds. – Monies in the Fund shall first be used to meet the debt service
4 obligations supported by the General Fund. In addition to meeting the debt service obligations
5 supported by the General Fund, the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council may
6 allocate money from the Fund to provide financial assistance for the following purposes:
7 (1) New capital projects for facilities licensed under this Chapter or Chapter 122C
8 of the General Statutes that are located in rural areas of the State.
9 (2) Repair and renovation projects for existing facilities licensed under this
10 Chapter or Chapter 122C of the General Statutes that are located in rural areas
11 of the State.
12 (3) Other healthcare infrastructure projects located in rural areas of the State
13 determined by the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council to be
14 consistent with the intent of the General Assembly, as specified in subsection
15 (a) of this section.
16 (4) Administrative costs incurred by the North Carolina State Health
17 Coordinating Council for administering the Fund, provided that such costs
18 shall not exceed one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000) in any fiscal year.
19 (d) Unexpended Funds. – Funds appropriated for a project that are unspent and
20 unencumbered upon completion of the project shall revert to the Fund. For the purposes of this
21 subsection, a project includes any allocation from the Fund for a purpose specified in subsection
22 (c) of this section.
23 (e) Report. – Annually on March 1, the North Carolina State Health Coordinating
24 Council shall report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services
25 and the Fiscal Research Division on the use of funds allocated from the Fund. The report shall
26 include at least all of the following information for the preceding fiscal year:
27 (1) Amounts credited to the Fund.
28 (2) Amounts expended from the Fund and the purposes of the expenditures,
29 including, at a minimum:
30 a. A description of each project funded and for each project, the location
31 and the type and amount of financial assistance provided.
32 b. A detailed list of administrative costs incurred by the North Carolina
33 State Health Coordinating Council for administering the Rural
34 Healthcare Infrastructure Fund.
35 (3) Proposed expenditures of the monies in the Fund for the current and upcoming
36 fiscal years.
37 (4) Any other information the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council
38 deems relevant to the financial sustainability of the Fund.
39 "§§ 131E-74.1 through 131E-74.25. Reserved for future codification purposes."
40 SECTION 1.1.(c) The North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council shall not
41 begin awarding financial assistance from the Rural Healthcare Infrastructure Fund created by
42 G.S. 131E-74, as enacted by subsection (b) of this section, until the plan for a Rural Healthcare
43 Infrastructure Program developed by the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council
44 pursuant to Part II of this act has been approved by an act of the General Assembly.
45 SECTION 1.2. Section 1.1(c) of this Part is effective when it becomes law.
46
47 PART II. PLAN FOR RURAL HEALTHCARE INFRASTRUCTURE PROGRAM
48 SECTION 2.1.(a) By January 15, 2027, the North Carolina State Health
49 Coordinating Council, in consultation with the Office of Rural Health of the Department of
50 Health and Human Services, shall develop and submit to the Joint Legislative Oversight
51 Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division a plan for the North
Page 2 DRH40672-MGa-162A

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 Carolina State Health Coordinating Council to establish and administer a Rural Healthcare
2 Infrastructure Program (the program) funded by the Rural Healthcare Infrastructure Fund created
3 by G.S. 131E-74, as enacted by Section 1.1(b) of this act (the Fund). The purpose of the program
4 is to award financial assistance from the Fund in the form of grants and loans at below market
5 interest rates with structured repayment terms to support the construction, renovation, or
6 modernization of healthcare infrastructure located in rural areas of the State. The plan shall
7 include recommendations for at least all of the following:
8 (1) An application process, including factors to be considered in approving or
9 denying applications for financial assistance from the Fund.
10 (2) A description of the entities and projects eligible to receive financial
11 assistance from the Fund.
12 (3) A description of what constitutes healthcare infrastructure located in a rural
13 area of the State for the purposes of the program.
14 (4) A process for evaluating the financial viability and sustainability of projects
15 seeking financial assistance from the Fund.
16 (5) A process for overseeing funds awarded from the Rural Healthcare
17 Infrastructure Fund.
18 (6) A process for ensuring compliance with contractual obligations and
19 performance indicators established for recipients of financial assistance.
20 (7) A long-term plan for financial sustainability of the Fund, including the
21 identification of all potential State and federal sources of funding.
22 (8) Any legislative changes necessary to implement the Rural Healthcare
23 Infrastructure Program.
24 (9) The amount of State appropriations needed to establish and administer the
25 Rural Healthcare Infrastructure Program.
26 (10) Any other information the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council
27 deems relevant to implementing the program and administering the Fund.
28 SECTION 2.1.(b) The North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council shall not
29 implement the plan developed pursuant to subsection (a) of this section without an act by the
30 General Assembly.
31 SECTION 2.2. This Part is effective when it becomes law.
32
33 PART III. ADJUSTMENTS TO THE NORTH CAROLINA STATE HEALTH
34 COORDINATING COUNCIL
35 SECTION 3.1.(a) G.S. 131E-191.1 reads as rewritten:
36 "§ 131E-191.1. Lobbyists prohibited from serving on the North Carolina State Health
37 Coordinating Council.Council; powers and duties; composition; qualifications
38 of members; terms; removal; vacancies; quorum; per diem.
39 (a) Powers and Duties. – The North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council has the
40 following powers and duties:
41 (1) To work with the Department to prepare a State Medical Facilities Plan for
42 approval by the Governor, as provided by G.S. 131E-176.2.
43 (2) To administer the Rural Healthcare Infrastructure Fund created by
44 G.S. 131E-74.
45 (b) Composition. – The North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council shall consist
46 of the following 25 members:
47 (1) Thirteen members appointed by the Governor as follows:
48 a. One at-large member.
49 b. One representative of medical educators.
50 c. One representative of hospices.
51 d. One representative of local health departments.
DRH40672-MGa-162A Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 e. One individual licensed to practice medicine in this State.
2 f. One representative of small businesses operating within the State that
3 employ fewer than 50 employees on a full-time basis.
4 g. One representative of large businesses operating within the State that
5 employ more than 50 employees on a full-time basis.
6 h. One representative of health insurers.
7 i. One representative of urban local governments.
8 j. One representative of rural local governments.
9 k. One representative of nursing homes licensed to operate in this State.
10 l. One representative of hospitals licensed to operate in this State.
11 m. One representative of home care agencies licensed to operate in this
12 State.
13 (2) Twelve at-large members appointed by the General Assembly in accordance
14 with G.S. 120-121, six upon the recommendation of the President Pro
15 Tempore of the Senate and six upon the recommendation of the Speaker of
16 the House of Representatives.
17 No person registered as a lobbyist under Chapter 120C of the General Statutes shall be
18 appointed to or serve on the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council. No person
19 previously registered as a lobbyist under Chapter 120C of the General Statutes shall be appointed
20 to or serve on the North Carolina State Health Coordinating Council within 120 days after the
21 expiration of the lobbyist's registration.
22 (c) Chair. – The members shall elect a chair who shall preside for the duration of the
23 chair's term as a member. In the event a vacancy occurs in the chair before the expiration of the
24 chair's term, the members shall elect an acting chair to serve for the remainder of the unexpired
25 term.
26 (d) Length of Terms. – Members appointed to the Council shall serve for a term of three
27 years. At the end of the respective terms of office of members of the Council, their successors
28 shall be appointed for terms of three years. Any appointment to fill a vacancy on the Council
29 created by the resignation, dismissal, death, or disability of a member shall be filled by the
30 appointing authority for the balance of the unexpired term. As used in this section, the term
31 "appointing authority" means the General Assembly in the case of members appointed by the
32 General Assembly and the Governor in the case of members appointed by the Governor.
33 (e) Removal of Members. – Each appointing authority may remove any member
34 appointed by that appointing authority for misfeasance, malfeasance, or nonfeasance.
35 (f) Filling of Vacancies. – Vacancies on the Council among the membership appointed
36 by the General Assembly shall be filled by the General Assembly as provided in subdivision
37 (b)(2) of this section for the unexpired term. Vacancies on the Council among the membership
38 appointed by the Governor shall be filled by the Governor for the unexpired term.
39 (g) Quorum. – A majority of the members of the Council constitutes a quorum for the
40 transaction of business.
41 (h) Per Diem and Expenses. – The members of the Council shall receive per diem and
42 necessary traveling and subsistence expenses in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 138-5.
43 (i) Administrative Assistance. – The Secretary of Health and Human Services shall
44 supply all clerical and other services required by the Council."
45 SECTION 3.1.(b) To minimize the impact of this section on the work of the North
46 Carolina State Health Coordinating Council (the Council), the Governor shall not appoint
47 successors to two members of the Council representing the General Assembly whose terms
48 expire December 31, 2026; shall not appoint successors to four members of the Council whose
49 terms expire December 31, 2026; shall not appoint successors to two at-large members of the
50 Council whose terms expire December 31, 2027; and shall not appoint successors to four at-large
51 members of the Council whose terms expire December 31, 2028. Instead, the General Assembly
